translate:
Forging iron to make fishhooks, I sell my books;
Drinking wine, I leave it to my servants to pay.
I fish and fish at the front of the steps;
Little knowing that clouds and mist adorn my pillow.
Dark springs flow from rocks, gurgling and murmuring;
Small paths meander, straight and then winding.
Bamboo at the window has not yet sprouted this summer;
Court peaches once bore flowers in bygone years.
My name is not yet as famous as Tao Hongjing's;
My beard and hair have turned white like Jiang Ya's.
The pine, moon, and water mists remain for a thousand years;
Who will possess them in the end, we cannot tell.

Visiting the Mystical Cave Heaven, I leave behind worldly attachments.
Deep in the wild grass, I suspect all could be herbs;
Quietly observing the woodcutters, I fear they might be immortals.
The green trees reach the clouds, growing old alone;
Ancient stone tablets lie across the water, unknown for ages.
Alas, the secluded scenery is worthy of long-lasting visits;
Letting the years pass by as humanity evolves.

With the pen near the fragrant flowers, I am not content;
I hasten to compose verses, eager for the enchanting season.
Alarmed by the common words, I feel ashamed;
Hastily reciting the elevated verse, my guilt is known.
The legendary purity of her name should be cherished more;
Her laughter, worth a thousand gold pieces, is hard to move.
Even in drunken songs and dances, we can admire;
In our old age, being foolish is truly a blessing.
